    {
      "id": "luz2v4dp",
      "questionNumber": 9,
      "questionText": "<p>Relative stability of the contributing structures is :</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1luz10nw2/f1a667eb-5368-4664-99dc-c28b52242d49/85a3a430-fa17-11ee-b660-8fcb8bd681fc/file-1luz10nw3.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1luz10nw2/f1a667eb-5368-4664-99dc-c28b52242d49/85a3a430-fa17-11ee-b660-8fcb8bd681fc/file-1luz10nw3.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"JEE Main 2024 (Online) 9th April Morning Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 83 English\"></p>",
      "options": [
        "(II) > (I) > (III)",
        "(III) > (II) > (I)",
        "(I) > (III) > (II)",
        "(I) > (II) > (III)"
      ],
      "correctOption": 3,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "stability-of-intermediate",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>Firstly higher the number of bonds or say complete octet higher will be stability, then the negative charge situated over more electronegative element more will be stability. Hence, overall order of stability is I > II > III.</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
